<div class="container">

  <div class="section">

  <h2>Setup Instructions</h2>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="span8">
      <h3>1. Link to your various social profiles on your home page</h3>

      <p>On your home page, link to your profiles and add the <code>rel="me"</code> attribute to the links.</p>
      <p>You'll want to make sure that your input formats are set to Full HTML or another format that
      will accept attributes if you're using a CMS.</p>

      <p>This may look something like the following:
      <pre><code><%== 
'<ul>
  <li><a href="https://twitter.com/aaronpk" rel="me">@aaronpk on Twitter</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/aaronpk" rel="me">Github</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://profiles.google.com/aaron.parecki" rel="me">Google</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://facebook.com/aaronpk" rel="me">Facebook</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/aaronpk/" rel="me">Flickr</a></li>
</ul>
' %></code></pre>
      </p>

    </div><!-- span -->
    <div class="span4">
      <ul class="thumbnails">
        <li><a class="thumbnail" href="#"><img src="/img/social-profiles.png" width="214" height="256" /></a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div><!-- row -->

  <div class="row">
    <div class="span8">
      <h3>2. On each service, ensure there is a link back to your home page</h3>

      <p>
        You'll need to verify that each service has a link back to your home page. For convenience the "edit profile" links for all the supported services are below.

        <div style="float: right;"><img src="/img/twitter-website-settings.png" width="394" height="102" /></div>

        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://twitter.com/settings/profile">Twitter</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://plus.google.com/me/about/edit/d">Google</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/settings/profile">Github</a></li>
          <li><a href="http://www.flickr.com/profile_edit.gne">Flickr</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://geoloqi.com/account/profile">Geoloqi</a></li>
        </ul>

      </p>
    </div>
  </div><!-- row -->

  <div class="row">
    <div class="span8">
      <h3>3. You're done!</h3>
      <p>That's it! You're done! Now you can use your domain to sign in to any sites that support IndieAuth!</p>
      
      <p> Github seems to be the most reliable service at this point in time. (July 2012) Twitter, Google and Flickr's APIs have changed, we're working on resolving those issues.</p>
      <p> If you're getting errors with 'No Valid Authentication Provider found', try using a different service.</p>
  
    </div>
  </div><!-- row -->


  </div><!-- section -->

</div><!-- container -->

